studyDesigns.rationale: Protocol-defined study design for investigating efficacy and safety

arms.name: Arm A: Rd
arms.description: Lenalidomide and Dexamethasone (Rd) alone. Lenalidomide 25 mg PO Days 1-21 of each 28-day cycle; Dexamethasone 40 mg weekly.

arms.name: Arm B: DRd
arms.description: Daratumumab, Lenalidomide, and Dexamethasone (DRd). Daratumumab 16 mg/kg IV (or 1800 mg SC) added to the Rd regimen.

analysisPopulations.name: Intent-to-Treat Analysis Set
analysisPopulations.text: The ITT analysis set includes all subjects who are randomized in the study. In this analysis set, subjects will be analyzed according to the treatment group to which they were randomized regardless of the treatment they actually received.
analysisPopulations.label: ITT
analysisPopulations.populationDescription: The ITT analysis set includes all subjects who are randomized in the study. In this analysis set, subjects will be analyzed according to the treatment group to which they were randomized regardless of the treatment they actually received.

analysisPopulations.name: Safety Analysis Set
analysisPopulations.text: The safety analysis set includes all subjects who received at least one dose of study treatment. In this analysis set, subjects will be analyzed according to the treatment they actually received.
analysisPopulations.label: SAF
analysisPopulations.populationDescription: The safety analysis set includes all subjects who received at least one dose of study treatment. In this analysis set, subjects will be analyzed according to the treatment they actually received.
analysisPopulations.criteria: Received at least one dose of study treatment

analysisPopulations.name: Per-Protocol Analysis Set
analysisPopulations.text: The per-protocol analysis set is a subset of the ITT analysis set, excluding subjects with major protocol deviations that may impact the efficacy outcomes. Major protocol deviations will be defined and subjects will be identified for exclusion from the PP analysis set prior to the clinical cut-off for the primary analysis.
analysisPopulations.label: PP
analysisPopulations.populationDescription: The per-protocol analysis set is a subset of the ITT analysis set, excluding subjects with major protocol deviations that may impact the efficacy outcomes. Major protocol deviations will be defined and subjects will be identified for exclusion from the PP analysis set prior to the clinical cut-off for the primary analysis.
analysisPopulations.criteria: ITT subset AND no major protocol deviations

analysisPopulations.name: Pharmacokinetic Analysis Set
analysisPopulations.text: The PK analysis set includes all subjects who received at least one dose of daratumumab and have at least one evaluable post-infusion PK sample.
analysisPopulations.label: PK
analysisPopulations.populationDescription: The PK analysis set includes all subjects who received at least one dose of daratumumab and have at least one evaluable post-infusion PK sample.
analysisPopulations.criteria: Received >=1 dose of daratumumab AND >=1 evaluable post-infusion PK sample

titles.text: A Phase 3 Study Comparing Daratumumab, Lenalidomide, and Dexamethasone (DRd) vs Lenalidomide and Dexamethasone (Rd) in Subjects with Previously Untreated Multiple Myeloma who are Ineligible for High Dose Therapy

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Age requirement
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Subjects who are 18 years of age

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Diagnosis and CRAB criteria
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Subject must have documented multiple myeloma satisfying the CRAB (calcium elevation, renal insufficiency, anemia and bone abnormalities) criteria (see Attachment 1), monoclonal plasma cells in the bone marrow 10% or presence of a biopsy proven plasmacytoma, and measurable disease.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Measurable disease
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Measurable disease, as assessed by central laboratory, defined by any of the following: IgG myeloma: Serum monoclonal paraprotein (M-protein) level 1.0 g/dL or urine M-protein level 200 mg/24 hours; or IgA, IgM, IgD, or IgE multiple myeloma: serum M-protein level 0.5 g/dL or urine M-protein level 200 mg/24 hours; or Light chain multiple myeloma without measurable disease in serum or urine: Serum immunoglobulin free light chain 10 mg/dL and abnormal serum immunoglobulin kappa lambda free light chain ratio.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Performance Status
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: An ECOG performance status score of 0, 1, or 2

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Transplant Ineligibility
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Must be newly diagnosed and not considered candidates for high-dose chemotherapy with stem cell transplantation (SCT).

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Hepatic Function
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Total bilirubin 2.0 x ULN, except in subjects with congenital bilirubinemia, such as Gilbert syndrome (direct bilirubin 2.0 x ULN)

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Renal Function
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Creatinine clearance 30 mL/min. Creatinine clearance can be calculated using the Cockcroft-Gault formula; or for subjects with over- or underweight, creatinine clearance may be measured from a 24-hours urine collection.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Calcium Levels
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Corrected serum calcium 14 mg/dL (3.5 mM/L); or free ionized calcium 6.5 mg/dL (1.6 mM/L)

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Contraception - Women
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Women of childbearing potential must commit to either abstain continuously from heterosexual sexual intercourse or to use 2 methods of reliable birth control simultaneously. Contraception must begin 4 weeks prior to dosing and must continue for 3 months after the last dose of daratumumab.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Sperm Donation - Men
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Men must not donate sperm for 3 months after the last dose of daratumumab.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Prior Steroid Dose
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Exclusion of prior treatment equivalent of dexamethasone 40 mg/day for a maximum 4 days.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: COPD Exclusion
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Subject has known chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) with a Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 second (FEV1) <50% of predicted normal.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Asthma Exclusion
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Subject has had known moderate or severe persistent asthma within the last 2 years, or currently has uncontrolled asthma of any classification.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Infectious Disease Serology
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Subject is known to be seropositive for human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) or hepatitis B (defined by a positive test for hepatitis B surface antigen [HBsAg] or antibodies to hepatitis B surface and core antigens [anti-HBs and anti-HBc, respectively]) or hepatitis C (anti-HCV antibody positive or HCV-RNA quantitation positive).

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Cardiac Disease
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Subject has clinically significant cardiac disease, including: myocardial infarction within 1 year, unstable/uncontrolled disease (unstable angina, CHF NYHA Class III-IV), uncontrolled cardiac arrhythmia (NCI CTCAE Grade 2), or QTcF >470 msec.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: Pregnancy and Fathering
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Revised pregnancy timing and for men not to father a child for 3 months after last dose of daratumumab.

eligibilityCriterionItems.name: SLiM CRAB Exclusion
eligibilityCriterionItems.text: Subjects only meeting SLiM CRAB are not eligible.

studyInterventions.name: Daratumumab
studyInterventions.description: Human IgG1 monoclonal antibody that binds to CD38.

studyInterventions.name: Lenalidomide
studyInterventions.description: Standard of care therapy for multiple myeloma administered in both Arm A and Arm B.

studyInterventions.name: Dexamethasone
studyInterventions.description: Corticosteroid administered in both Arm A and Arm B; also used as pre-dose medication.

studyInterventions.name: Acetaminophen/paracetamol
studyInterventions.description: Required pre-dose medication to prevent infusion-related reactions.

studyInterventions.name: Antihistamine
studyInterventions.description: Required pre-dose medication (e.g., diphenhydramine) to prevent infusion-related reactions.

studyInterventions.name: Aspirin
studyInterventions.description: Recommended prophylaxis for deep vein thrombosis and pulmonary embolism.

studyInterventions.name: Low molecular weight heparin
studyInterventions.description: Recommended prophylaxis for venous thromboembolism in high-risk subjects.

studyInterventions.name: Clarithromycin
studyInterventions.description: Prohibited therapy due to potential anti-multiple myeloma effects.

amendments.name: Amendment 9
amendments.summary: To define the clinical cut-off for the final CSR analysis. This cut-off will mark the start of the long-term survival follow-up during which subjects will continue to receive study treatment and will be followed for overall survival (OS). Additionally, this amendment revises the end of study definition and defines the timing of the final overall survival (OS)analysis cut-off. This amendment also provides clarification that subjects who are benefiting from study treatment will be able to continue to receive study treatment from the final OS analysis until the end of study when alternative access to daratumumab is not available.

amendments.name: Amendment 8
amendments.summary: Text is added to clarify timing of urine collection for M-protein analysis, modify imaging assessments for lytic disease, and add a list of anticipated events consistent with other daratumumab studies. It also provides clarifications regarding CRAB criteria eligibility and minor follow-up window adjustments.

commentAnnotations.text: Janssen Research & Development is a global organization that operates through different legal entities in various countries. The term 'sponsor' represents these various legal entities.
After Study MMY3008 transitions to long-term survival follow-up, an end-of-treatment visit is no longer required.
Pharmacokinetic and anti-daratumumab antibody sampling is no longer required for subjects in Treatment Arm B who remain on daratumumab IV therapy.
Immunohistochemistry or immunofluorescence or 2- to 4-color flow cytometry are acceptable methods to evaluate plasma cell clonality.
Trained study staff at the clinic should be prepared to intervene in case of any infusion-related reactions occurring, and resources necessary for resuscitation must be available at the bedside.

studyDefinitionDocumentVersions.description: To define the clinical cut-off for the final CSR analysis and transition to long-term survival follow-up.
To provide flexibility during the COVID-19 pandemic, including the option to switch to subcutaneous daratumumab.
Clarifications to study conduct and alignment with updates in all daratumumab protocols.
Response to identification of a new important risk (hepatitis B virus reactivation).
Allowing subjects in Arm A access to daratumumab after sponsor confirmation of disease progression.

studyAmendmentImpacts.affectedSection: Synopsis; Section 3.1; Section 10.1; Section 11.2; Section 11.3; Section 17.9.1
studyAmendmentImpacts.description: Defined clinical cut-off for final CSR analysis, transition to long-term survival follow-up, and final OS analysis timing.
Clarified permitted and prohibited vaccinations, specifically restricting live-attenuated vaccines.
Introduced Subcutaneous (SC) administration of daratumumab as an alternative to IV during the COVID-19 pandemic.
Added monitoring and management requirements for Hepatitis B Virus (HBV) reactivation.

studyAmendmentReasons.reasonText: To define the clinical cut-off for the final CSR analysis and revise the end of study definition.
To provide flexibility for study investigators to prioritize patient safety during the global COVID-19 pandemic.
In response to identification of a new important risk (hepatitis B virus [HBV] reactivation).
Following review of data from the second interim analysis by the IDMC, allowing Arm A subjects access to daratumumab.

studyChanges.summary: Updated terminology to distinguish between final OS analysis and end of study.

studyChanges.afterText: Second primary malignancies added to medically important events.
studyChanges.summary: Expanded definition of medically important serious adverse events.
Added new section for subcutaneous administration procedures.
Removed severity definitions to rely solely on NCI-CTCAE Version 4.03.

studyChanges.afterText: Subjects whose dose was delayed for more than 4 weeks (Cycle 1 to Cycle 6) or more than 6 weeks (Cycle 7 and beyond) should have study treatment discontinued
studyChanges.summary: Clarified specific timeframes for treatment discontinuation due to dose delays.
